3. Recommended Product Scope
Public-Facing Website
The public-facing site should include:
Home
About / History
Public Events Calendar
Projects / Community Impact
Scholarships
Donate
Contact
Social links
Photo gallery / archive
Public content areas should clearly support:
upcoming events
local identity and belonging
credibility
donation trust
record of impact
Known important stories/examples:
public park restroom project
Gagaball pit
awarded scholarships
event calendar
photographs of community efforts
Members Area
The members area should stay intentionally lightweight and focused on practical operations:
member-only calendar
announcements / bulletin board
simple discussion forum / thread-based message board
profile/account basics
role-aware access control
officer/admin moderation tools
Explicit Non-Goals for MVP
Do not build these in the first release unless there is a compelling need:
real-time chat
custom mobile app
complex workflow automation
advanced analytics dashboard
heavy CMS integration
overcomplicated roles and permissions
event ticketing platform
custom donation ledger system
granular audit engine
social network features
---
4. Recommended Technical Direction
Right-Sized Stack
Use a modern but boring stack:
Next.js with App Router
TypeScript
PostgreSQL
Prisma ORM
NextAuth / Auth.js or similarly practical auth solution
Tailwind CSS
Stripe for donations
Resend or similarly simple email provider for contact and auth flows
Vercel-friendly deployment
Why This Stack
This combination is:
popular
well-supported
readable
fast to scaffold
realistic for a solo maintainer
secure enough when implemented responsibly
flexible without becoming a burden
Admin / Content Management Direction
Default to a simple protected admin area inside the app instead of introducing a full CMS immediately.
Reason:
fewer moving parts
less configuration burden
easier to understand
better aligned with a modest content footprint
Only add a CMS later if the team feels real content bottlenecks.
---
5. Prompt Strategy Best Practices
When using Copilot, do not ask it to “build the whole product” in one shot.
Use prompts that:
set firm constraints
define scope clearly
establish architecture early
sequence work in manageable chunks
ask for implementation in an opinionated order
require brief tradeoff explanations
require readable code and filenames
emphasize security and maintainability
Each prompt below is written to reduce:
architectural drift
accidental complexity
random dependency choices
UI chaos
weak auth assumptions
bloated feature creep
